Revision history for App-Baphomet

        - The bsd_syslog grammar now reads a relayed IPv6 hostname instead
          of mangling it into the daemon slot, and reads the RFC 3339
          timestamp form rsyslog's default file format chisels. The
          ietf_syslog grammar accepts RFC-valid escaped quotes inside
          structured data param values. Both grammars reject a PRI past
          191 as not syslog at all, via the new shared pri_decompose in
          App::Baphomet::Parser. The json_syslog and journal parsers now
          read a present-but-empty MESSAGE as a parsed line with a empty
          message, matching the text grammars... a missing MESSAGE is
          still unparsed, being the evidence the line is syslog shaped.
        - baphomet stop no longer misreads a root-owned manager as dead
          when run as non-root... kill 0 answering EPERM now counts as
          alive.
        - Load-time condition checks... a *-pattern quantifier target
          covering no selections, a N of threshold past the selection
          count, and 0 of are all load errors now instead of silently
          vacuous or unfireable conditions. A unknown tests section name
          (a typo'd positive, say) is a load error rather than zero tests
          and a clean load, and the rules cache no longer hands a rule
          first loaded with skip_tests to a caller wanting the tests
          without running them.
        - Galla state keeping... positions for files gone from disk and no
          longer followed are pruned at snapshot, so dated glob logs do
          not pile up in the tablet forever. The CSV escaper drops
          newlines rather than chiseling rows its loaders can not read
          back, and the cursors loader honors quoting instead of shearing
          at the first comma. The mark fold's value now rides with
          whichever expiry won, ties folding lexically, so gallas draining
          the same events in different orders converge on one value. A
          distinct-counted offender feeds its subnet bucket like any
          other.
        - The redis clay tablet logs a failed mark publish instead of
          swallowing it, sets its Redis client name from the galla name as
          intended, and round-trips trailing empty tablet lines the same
          as the file backend. A CamelCase ClayTablet backend name is used
          as written, so a third-party SQLite stays reachable.
        - galla --help and --version exit 0 and a missing --name is a
          clean usage error. baphomet status of one galla traps a dead
          socket like the other commands, answering partial status with a
          error instead of a raw die. Constructors bless into the class
          they were called as, so subclassing works.
        - Kur-level log/parser/rule/join keys are errors now instead of
          silently accepted and unapplied... the kur and watcher allowed
          key sets are built from one shared list so they can not drift
          apart again. The config POD gained the missing top-level keys
          (the subnet four, allow_per_rule_thresholds, eve_only,
          observe_ignored, default_severity) and watcher keys (journal,
          join, the overrides).

        - Keywords standing alone as a rule's whole boolean matcher now
          actually judge the found on the syslog and raw types... the guard
          before the matcher only knew gates and conditions, so a rule with
          only keywords silently skipped them, on flat and staged rules both.
          The message_json banish-every-line load check likewise now counts
          keywords as a matcher, matching its json and http siblings.
        - A watcher key of journal = false now means no journal at all
          rather than follow-the-whole-journal... TOML false is a defined
          value, so it once classified the watcher as a journal one with no
          matches. New watcher_is_journal in App::Baphomet::Config.
        - The file clay tablet checks its writes and its close before the
          rename, so a full disk fails the write loudly instead of swapping
          a truncated tablet in over the good one.
        - The stats counters born at runtime (joined, alerts, subnet_bans,
          subnet_alerts, hostname_dropped, dns_failures, rdns_failures) are
          now in the stats template, so a respawned galla restores them from
          the tablet instead of silently dropping them to zero.

0.0.1	2026-07-12
        - The gate, selections/condition, and keywords/%%%ANY%%% boolean
          matcher reaches the http and http_error types too, so the operators,
          decode, boolean composition, and keyword search are now on every rule
          type. Each runs its generic gate as a pre-filter over the parsed
          fields (host/method/path/status/... for http, client/level/module/
          message for http_error), ANDed with the type's own status/method or
          level/module gates and its matches. The types' internal status/method
          and level/module store moved to field_gates to free the shared gate
          slot; existing http and http_error rules are unchanged. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::HTTP and App::Baphomet::Rules::HTTPError.
        - Keyword search across fields. A gate or selection predicate may name
          the reserved field %%%ANY%%% to fan itself over every field value at
          once (and the message on syslog/raw), or %%%ANY:prefix%%% to fan only
          over a subtree, so a string is searched everywhere or just a known
          branch without touching the rest. The operators and decode all work
          over the fan, and a negate means the string is in no field. The
          keywords shorthand is sugar... a plain list searches every field, the
          { in, values } table scopes it to a path, a subtree, or all. Keywords
          AND ahead of any gate or selections. On json, syslog, and raw. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::JSON.
        - value_count, distinct with a grouping key. The distinct spec gained
          an optional by field, so counting groups by any field rather than
          always the offender... count(of) by (by). With no by it is the built
          distinct-cardinality, keyed by the offender and banishing it. With a
          by the set is keyed by that field and the current offender is
          banished instead, since the key may not be bannable, so N distinct
          sources against one account (distributed spray) banishes the source
          that tips it over, not the account. A by-keyed set does not reset on
          firing, so every further source is caught while the key stays over
          threshold; the set is bounded per key. Pairs with eve_only for
          detect-only, and generalizes the marks-based sshd-spray pair into one
          declarative rule. See App::Baphomet::Rules::Syslog.
        - Temporal correlation, the sequence gate. Marks gained a first-seen
          set time, and a rule may carry a sequence gate, an array of entries
          each naming a list of marks that must all be set for the key and in
          the listed order by set time, keyed by a var's capture or the
          offender. So a run of mark_only rules branding stages, and a rule
          watching for them in sequence, fires only on an ordered attack chain
          (recon then foothold then exfil). A missing, expired, or out-of-order
          stage fails the gate; equal set times count as in order. The set time
          is checkpointed to the marks tablet and carried on the fleet mark sync
          bus (folded to the earliest across machines), so a fleet-shared
          sequence correlates stages seen on different hosts. Unordered
          correlation is still the plain marked gate over the same brands. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::Syslog.
        - Distinct-cardinality counting (TODO 5). A rule may carry a distinct
          spec, distinct: { of: FIELD }, switching its counting from summing
          hits to counting the distinct values of that field seen from an
          offender IP within find_time... the score is the set size, and the
          IP is banished when it reaches max_score distinct values. This is the
          credential-stuffing shape, N different usernames from one source,
          that per-hit counting can not tell from one username retried. Works
          on every rule type, its own bucket keyed by rule and IP, swept and
          checkpointed like the counters so a partial count rides a restart.
          See App::Baphomet::Rules::Syslog and the distinct tablet.
        - selections/condition reach the syslog and raw types. The boolean
          form (cut three) is no longer json-only... a syslog or raw rule may
          use named selections and a condition over its captures the same way
          it uses a gate, run as the post-match refinement. Gate and boolean
          compile and evaluation are now one shared path in Rules::Base for all
          three types.
        - message_json on syslog rules, the fourth Sigma cut. When a daemon
          logs a JSON object as its message, message_json: true decodes and
          flattens it into fields the gate tests by dotted path, so the
          operators and decode fall on the message's own fields... the syslog
          envelope reachable under reserved syslog.* keys, ban_var naming a
          json field or a capture. message_regexp is then optional, the gate
          matching; a non-json message yields no fields and falls through, and
          a present message_regexp still runs on the raw message as the matcher
          with the gate refining over both. The decode is memoised per line
          across rules. Opt-in, so rules without it are unchanged. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::Syslog.
        - Boolean rule logic on json rules... selections and a condition, the
          third Sigma cut. A rule may carry named selections, each a list of
          gate predicates ANDed, and a condition string composing them with
          and/or/not, parens, and the quantifiers "all of them", "1 of them",
          and "N of <prefix>_*". This is the pre-filter when present, giving
          the OR, arbitrary nested NOT, and N-of-M the flat gate cannot... the
          Sigma detection model. An alternative to gate (the two together are
          an error); a rule without selections runs the gate path unchanged.
          The condition parser and evaluator are in Rules::Base. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::JSON.
        - The gate operators and decode reach syslog and raw rules too. Those
          types gain an optional gate, a post-match refinement over the
          captures a message_regexp extracts... the same predicate form the
          json gate uses (legacy field/values, or op/value/all/negate/decode),
          run after the pattern matches, any failing predicate dropping the
          line to a non-offense. The field names a capture (a token like SRC,
          a named group like CMD) or the reserved MESSAGE for the whole
          message, so a rule can decode an extracted variable or the message
          itself. Composes with a future message_json. Gate compile and
          evaluation are now shared in Rules::Base; a rule with no gate is
          unchanged. See App::Baphomet::Rules::Syslog.
        - Decode/transform on json gate predicates, the second Sigma cut. A
          predicate may carry a decode list run left to right over the field
          value before the operator, so an obfuscated payload is compared
          decoded... base64, base64offset (the three alignment candidates),
          utf16le/utf16be/utf16 (wide aliasing utf16le), windash, url, lower,
          upper. A transform that cannot decode drops that candidate, so a bad
          decode simply misses; decode: [ base64, utf16le ] with op contains
          is the PowerShell -enc shape. Opt-in on the predicate, so rules
          without it are unchanged.
        - Typed field operators on the json rule gate, the first cut of the
          Sigma-grade condition work. A gate entry may now use an operator
          form... op eq (default), contains, startswith, endswith, re (a
          tokened regexp), numeric gt/lt/ge/le, or cidr (v4/v6 membership,
          reusing the ignore-list machine), with value/values, an all flag
          for match-every rather than match-any, and negate (which holds when
          the field is absent, matching Sigma's field-absent semantics). The
          form is opt-in and detected by an op/value/all/negate key, so the
          legacy field/values equality-or-//regexp// gate is untouched and
          every shipped rule and its tests are unchanged. See
          App::Baphomet::Rules::JSON.
        - Fleet-shared marks over Redis, a sync bus rather than a store. With
          the redis ClayTablet backend, a galla still holds its marks in
          memory and gates on them locally, but publishes each brand and lift
          to a per-scope Redis Stream and drains the fleet's on its sweep, so
          machines running the same kur converge... the account sprayed from a
          fresh source on another host now trips this host's marked gate. The
          reads never touch Redis, so an outage is invisible to the gates; a
          galla degrades to standalone marks and buffers un-published brands in
          an outbox that flushes on reconnect. The backend connects fast-fail
          and reconnects on its own throttle, so a down or absent Redis never
          hangs startup. It optionally wraps the file backend
          (ClayTablet.options.local) so the host-local tablets persist to disk,
          letting a galla that loses the bus and is restarted while it is still
          gone resume its whole state locally. Deltas fold in stream order with
          extend-only expiry, so the fold converges without locking. New
          options: scope, mark_max_ttl, host, local, cnx_timeout, outbox_max.
          Off unless the redis backend is chosen. See App::Baphomet::ClayTablet::Redis.
        - Pluggable state tablet storage. A galla's per-galla tablets
          (counters, pending bans, log positions, journal cursors, stats,
          correlation context, and marks) now go through a pluggable backend,
          the ClayTablet frontend, chosen by a new global [ClayTablet] table:
          .ClayTablet.backend names the backend and .ClayTablet.options is the
          free-form table it interprets. The default is the "file" backend,
          the current on-disk system, byte-for-byte unchanged, so an absent
          [ClayTablet] table and every existing config keep working; the
          tablet_base_dir setting stays its base dir. A "redis" backend ships,
          built on the optional Redis::Fast, keeping each tablet as one key
          under <prefix>:tablet:<galla>:<kind> so a fleet can share a store
          off the local disk. The shared banishment ledger is not a per-galla
          tablet and stays a file. See App::Baphomet::ClayTablet.
        - Severity and classification metadata on rules and EVE, the rest of
          the Suricata/Sagan alert set beside msg. Rules may carry severity
          (info/low/medium/high/critical), classtype (a Snort/Sagan category
          string), references (URLs/CVEs), and attack (MITRE ATT&CK ids), all
          inert to matching and written to EVE as top-level fields when set.
          severity falls back to a new config default_severity (global/kur/
          watcher) when a rule sets none, else the field is omitted; the other
          three are omitted when unset. Every shipped rule was backfilled with
          a severity and classtype. This turns the EVE stream from a flat run
          of matches into triageable detections.
        - A msg on rules and EVE. A rule may carry a msg, the Sagan/Suricata
          human-readable signature ("[TAG] description"), written to every EVE
          event it produces as the top-level .msg field... Suricata's
          alert.signature, promoted, so tooling reads what tripped without
          decoding the raw line. Absent, it falls back to the rule name, so
          .msg is always present. Every shipped rule was backfilled with one.
          Inert to matching.
        - BREAKING: max_retrys is renamed max_score, everywhere it appeared...
          the config setting (global, kur, watcher), the per-rule override,
          the recidive table, and every shipped rule. Rename it in your
          config and any local rules. It now reads as a score to reach, not
          a retry count.
        - Weighted scoring. A rule may carry a weight, a positive number
          defaulting to 1, and max_score is the accumulated score at which an
          offender is banished. Each match deposits its rule's weight, so a
          dangerous signature can weigh 10 and banish on one hit while a noisy
          one weighs 1, and several rules against one IP sum toward the one
          threshold (sshguard's model) instead of racing separate counters.
          With every weight 1 the score is the old count exactly. Weight is
          honored under the same allow_per_rule_thresholds consent as the
          thresholds. The counters tablet grew a weight column, old rows
          restoring at 1; baphomet accused now shows hits and score both; the
          EVE count field is renamed score.
        - Observe mode, eve_only. A rule, watcher, kur, or the whole
          deployment can be set eve_only (a rule's own layering over the
          watcher-resolved value, most-specific winning, so a deployment can
          observe globally and trusted rules opt back in with eve_only:
          false). An eve_only rule matches and writes to EVE but never
          banishes... a would-be ban becomes an alert event and each match a
          noted event, into a shadow counter kept wholly apart from the real
          ones. CrowdSec's simulation, per rule. observe_ignored (global, kur,
          watcher) widens observe mode to also score what ignore_ips would
          drop. Tested in t/weighted.t and t/eve-only.t.
        - The namtar_list gate reaches beyond IPs. A namtar_lists entry may
          now be a typed table, {type = "string", files = ..., nocase = ...},
          declaring a string list matched by exact (optionally case-folded)
          equality instead of a CIDR list matched by address. Paired with a
          gate entry's var, a rule can count only when a captured username,
          URI, user-agent, or any other field is on a named roll... a
          honeypot-account or known-bad-path list, not just a threat feed of
          addresses. The bare path/array form stays a CIDR list, so existing
          config is unchanged. One entry may union lists of both flavors.
        - Four new syslog rules for daemons fail2ban does not cover, ported
          from Sagan: syslog/openvpn (auth/TLS handshake failures),
          syslog/postgresql (password auth failures... needs `%h` in
          log_line_prefix), syslog/samba (smbd connection denials), and
          syslog/rsyncd (rsync daemon module auth failures). Each needs the
          daemon logging through syslog. No engine changes... daemon gating,
          ban_var, and per-rule thresholds already carry them.
        - Renamed the consign vocabulary to banish, on theme for the
          underworld... the baphomet consigned command is now baphomet
          banished, the EVE event_type consign is now banish, and the shared
          ledger file is banishments.csv. Update anything that filtered EVE
          on event_type=consign or read consignments.csv.
        - baphomet stop now waits for the manager to actually exit before
          returning, up to the config timeout, so service baphomet restart
          no longer races the old PID file and aborts the start with
          "Pid_file already exists for running process". The manager's stop
          reply carries its PID for the wait; --no-wait and --timeout tune
          it. The FreeBSD rc passes --config to stop to match.
        - A active_time gate on rules... only count a match when the time is
          in, or not in, named time windows, so an offense routine at midday
          can be an alarm at 03:00. The windows are defined in the config's
          active_time (a {days, hours} spec or array of them per name),
          layered global/kur/watcher merged per name; days are 0..6, hours a
          HHMM-HHMM range that may wrap midnight. The gate is is/isnot over
          one or more window names (unioned), and optionally checks a found
          value's timestamp (epoch or ISO 8601) instead of the current time,
          failing closed on anything unparseable. Unlike the other gates it
          is whole-result, time being a property of the line not the
          offender. Local time. No shipped rule, as which hours matter is
          operator policy.
        - A namtar_list gate on rules... only count a match when a IP is on
          a named blocklist, the inverse of ignore_ips. The lists are CIDR
          files named in the config's namtar_lists (a path or array of
          paths per name), layered global/kur/watcher and reloaded on mtime
          change, so a threat feed that updates on disk takes effect with in
          a sweep. A gate entry names one or more lists (unioned) and an
          optional var to check instead of the offender, the same two-mode
          split as the country and mark gates. Fails closed on an address
          on no list or an unreadable feed, and ignore_ips still wins. No
          shipped rule, as which addresses are condemned is operator policy.
        - A country gate on rules... only count a match when the offender,
          or a named found var, is in (is) or not in (isnot) a set of
          countries, via a MaxMind GeoIP database (geoip_db, read through
          the optional IP::Geolocation::MMDB). Rules stay geography-neutral
          by importing named country-code lists with the
          %%%country_codes{name}%%% token; those lists live in the config
          (country_codes) at global, kur, and watcher level, merged per
          name. Without vars the gate filters offenders; with vars it
          checks the geography of other captured addresses and vetoes the
          whole result, so a rule can ban a flow's src only when its dest
          is one of yours. Fails closed on an unlocatable IP or a missing
          database, warning loudly at start. A loaded database also stamps
          the banished IP's country onto EVE banish events.
        - Marks... a galla wide, expiring, named store one rule brands and
          another gates on, so rules carry state across each other the way
          correlation carries it across lines (Sagan's xbits/flexbits).
          New rule keys on every type: mark and unmark set and lift brands,
          marked and not_marked gate on them, mark_only brands without
          counting or consuming the line. The key defaults to the offender
          IP but any capture or field can be it (var), and a value can be
          harvested from the line onto the brand (value_var), which a gate
          can then require to equal or differ from a capture (value_is/
          value_not). Marks live per galla, cross watchers and rules but
          not kurs, survive a restart via a new marks tablet, and are shown
          by the new baphomet marked command. Shipped with a demo pair,
          syslog/sshd-mark-users and syslog/sshd-spray, catching one
          account hit from more than one source... the distributed brute
          force per-IP counting can not see.
        - Per-rule thresholds, gated by the new allow_per_rule_thresholds
          setting (global, per kur, per watcher... off by default). With
          the flag on, a rule carrying its own max_score, find_time, or
          ban_time speaks over the watcher, the layering becoming rule
          over watcher over kur over global. A rule overriding how
          counting works gets its own counter bucket so its window does
          not touch the shared per-IP count, rides the counters tablet in
          a new third column (old tablets restore fine), and is broken
          out per rule by baphomet accused. Shipped rules now carry the
          numbers fail2ban's jail.conf gives their filters (shellshock,
          badbots, nagios, and portsentry at 1, the overflow/botsearch
          family at 2, asterisk and freeswitch at 10) and the priority 1
          Suricata classes plus suricata-blocked sit at 1... all inert
          until the flag consents.
        - Initial release. Log watcher for Ereshkigal... tails logs, parses
          syslog lines, matches them against YAML rules, and banishes
          offending IPs to Kur via the Ereshkigal manager socket.
        - 47 more rules ported from fail2ban, closing the filter library to
          essentially everything that is a regexp over a log line... more
          syslog daemons, a large raw batch of own-format app and webmail
          logs, more web rules, and slapd via keyed correlation. 135 rules
          shipped now.
        - Visibility commands matching what fail2ban shows... baphomet
          accused lists the IPs being counted but not yet banished, per
          IP the live hit count and first/last hit epochs, via a new
          accused action on the galla and manager sockets. baphomet
          banished asks Ereshkigal who Kur holds for the kurs this
          Baphomet feeds, expanding fan_out gates to their members and
          marking bans still pending delivery, with --ip answering which
          kurs hold a address. baphomet ledger reads the banishment
          history... when, which kur, which IP, by which rule and watcher,
          filterable by kur, IP, --since, and --tail.
        - The shared banishment ledger is now chiseled on every
          banishment, recidive or no, and carries rule and watcher
          columns. Retention is bounded by the new ledger_keep setting,
          30 days by default, 0 meaning forever, never pruning inside the
          recidive window.
        - Stats now break down per watcher and per rule alongside the
          galla-wide totals, and persist across restarts via a new stats
          tablet... totals mean since first loosing, not since the last
          respawn.
        - A optional Neti gate on the manager socket, the enable_auth unix
          ownership auth challenge gated by authed_users and authed_groups,
          matching Ereshkigal. socket_mode is now validated at load, and
          socket_group/socket_mode gate the manager socket as before.
        - A internal config field, global and per kur, marking your own
          hosts, and a ban_not_internal rule option banishing the end of
          a flow that is not internal. internal defaults to the ignore
          IPs. All the Suricata rules use it, so the offender is picked as
          the external end whether it is the src or the dest... the flow
          direction depends on where the alert fired.
        - json/suricata-blocked, banishing sources Suricata itself chose
          to block, per eve.json alert.action == "blocked".
        - A rule per Suricata classification class,
          json/suricata-<classtype>, gating on alert.category and
          banishing src_ip, so eve.json can be acted on class by class.
          43 of them, from Suricata's own classification.config.
        - An EVE event log, a Suricata-shaped NDJSON record of what the
          gallas do... found and banish events with eve_type baphomet,
          the raw and parsed line, the found data, a count, and the rule
          minus its tests. Path set by default, written only when
          eve_enable is on. See docs/eve.md.
        - A ignore_ips list, global and per kur, of addresses and CIDRs
          never banished no matter what the rules say.
        - Each galla persists its state to tablets under tablet_base_dir,
          /var/db/baphomet by default... counters, pending bans,
          correlation context, and log positions, checkpointed and
          restored, so a restart or crash does not forget an attacker
          mid-way and lines written while down are still read.
        - Native systemd journal support... a watcher takes a journal of
          journalctl matches instead of a log, followed via journalctl -o
          json, cursor persisted across restarts. The syslog rules apply
          to it unchanged.
        - Repeat offender escalation via the recidive table... every
          banishment is recorded to a shared ledger and a IP banished
          too many times across all kurs is dragged through a further gate
          to the recidive kur.
        - A migration guide for people coming from fail2ban, docs/fail2ban.md.
        - A watcher's log may be a array of files and entries may be
          globs, re-expanded every ten seconds while running, so new
          matches, like a freshly created jail, get picked up live.
        - Multiline support via keyed correlation... capture_regexp
          entries harvest context under a key, keyed message_regexp
          entries resolve through it or defer awaiting it, either order,
          TTL bounded and per watcher. Rule tests may be sequences via
          messages. Ships raw/mongodb-auth-legacy and completes
          sendmail-reject's No such user pair.
        - The json parser handles generic JSON application logs, whatever
          the schema, flattening nesting into dotted field paths matched
          by rules of the json type... field gates, per-field match and
          ignore regexps with tokens, and ban_var resolving either a
          capture or a field path. Ships json/mongodb-auth (the modern
          structured format), json/caddy-botsearch, and json/suricata,
          and a journalctl -o json example in the docs.
        - The raw parser is the no-op escape hatch, the whole line as the
          message, matched by rules of the raw type... syslog rules minus
          the daemon gate. Never format-sniffed, only explicitly
          configured. Ships raw/mysqld-auth, raw/exim, and raw/3proxy.
        - The apache_error and nginx_error parsers handle the web server
          error logs, matched by rules of the http_error type... level and
          module gates plus message regexps, banning the parsed client.
          nginx structured pairs are peeled into fields, rightmost wins
          against injection. Rules may set test_parser to default the
          parser for all their embedded tests.
        - The http_access parser handles common and combined HTTP access
          logs, matched by rules of the new http type... gates on status
          and method plus per-field match/ignore regexps, banning the
          client field. Ships http/badbots and http/botsearch. Rule types
          and parsers are cross-checked at start.
        - The syslog parser handles RFC 3164, RFC 5424, and the JSON
          output of syslog-ng (also available on its own as json_syslog),
          sniffed per line, and is the default when a watcher does not
          name a parser. Parsed lines carry a format key saying which
          won. The syslog rules apply to JSON logs unchanged.
        - Rules may carry ignore_regexp entries, the fail2ban ignoreregex
          equivalent, and a watcher's rule may be a array of rules checked
          first-match-wins, for logs carrying several daemons.
        - Licensed GPL-2.0-or-later, matching fail2ban, which the shipped
          rules are derived from.
        - Ships 25 syslog rules translated from the fail2ban filters, each
          carrying tests mined from the fail2ban test log corpus. See
          docs/rules-catalog.md.
